-- Jet Kerosene’s Premium to Gasoil Narrows; Fuel Oil (Correct)
-- B y   A n n   K o h
-- 2010-10-28T07:08:59Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-10-28/asian-jet-kerosene-s-premium-to-gasoil-narrows-fuel-oil-margins-decline.html
(Corrects changes in stockpiles in first paragraph.)  Asian jet fuel, a proxy for kerosene,
traded at the smallest premium to gasoil in almost three weeks
as heating-oil stockpiles in Japan climbed. Fuel-oil refining
margins were at the lowest in a week in Singapore.  Middle Distillates  Jet-kerosene’s premium over gasoil, or the regrade, shrank
to 95 cents a barrel at 9:56 a.m. Singapore time, according to
data from PVM Oil Associates. The spread is at its narrowest
since Oct. 11.  Processing profits from making gasoil gained 1 cent to
$12.39 a barrel in Singapore, PVM data showed. Gasoil swaps rose
0.3 percent to $93.10 a barrel.  Japan’s kerosene stockpiles climbed 112,021 kiloliters to
2.9 million kiloliters last week, the Petroleum Association of
Japan said yesterday.  Fuel Oil  Fuel oil’s discount to Dubai crude, or the crack spread,
widened to $6.71 a barrel in Singapore, the biggest discount
since Oct. 21, PVM data showed. Swaps for fuel oil rose 0.3
percent to $481 a metric ton.  A unit of the Singapore trade ministry is scheduled to
release data on oil stockpiles later today.  Naphtha  Naphtha for delivery to Japan rose relative to Brent crude
futures today. The premium was at $136.68 a ton from $134.55 at
the end of trading in Asia yesterday, according to calculations
based on Bloomberg data.  Open-specification naphtha cargoes delivered in the second
half of December were bid at $761.50 a metric ton against offers
at $764.50, according to data from Ginga Petroleum Singapore Pte.
First-half January lots were bid at $759.50 a ton compared with
offers at $762.50 a ton.  Naphtha for delivery from mid-December to mid-January was
at $759.50 a ton yesterday, according to data compiled by
Bloomberg.  Asian producers will experience another “two to four years
of pain” before refining margins improve significantly,
Satvinder Roopra, head of downstream oil at Wood Mackenzie Ltd.,
said yesterday.  To contact the reporter on this story:
